To create a Discord bot with a single `/ban` slash command using Discord.js v14, follow the steps below. In this example, I'll provide you with the code for a simplified version without extensive error handling or additional functionalities.

1. First, ensure you have Node.js and npm installed on your system.
2. Create a new directory for your project and initialize it with `npm init -y`.
3. Install the `discord.js` package by running `npm install discord.js`.
4. Create a file named `index.js` and add the following code:

```javascript
const { Client, Intents, SlashCommandBuilder } = require('discord.js');
const { REST } = require('@discordjs/rest');
const { Routes } = require('discord-api-types/v9');
const { token, clientId, guildId } = require('./config.json');

const client = new Client({
  intents: [
    Intents.FLAGS.GUILDS,
    Intents.FLAGS.GUILD_MESSAGES,
    Intents.FLAGS.GUILD_MEMBERS,
    Intents.FLAGS.GUILD_BANS,
    Intents.FLAGS.DIRECT_MESSAGES,
  ],
});

const banCommand = new SlashCommandBuilder()
  .setName('ban')
  .setDescription('Bans a member from the server.')
  .addUserOption((option) =>
    option.setName('user')
      .setDescription('The user to ban.')
      .setRequired(true)
  )
  .addStringOption((option) =>
    option.setName('reason')
      .setDescription('The reason for the ban.')
      .setRequired(false)
  );

const commands = [
  banCommand.build(),
];

const rest = new REST({ version: '9' }).setToken(token);

(async () => {
  try {
    console.log('Registering commands...');
    await rest.put(
      Routes.applicationGuildCommands(clientId, guildId),
      { body: commands },
    );
    console.log('Commands registered successfully.');
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
  }
})();

client.on('ready', () => {
  console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}!`);
});

client.on('interactionCreate', async (interaction) => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  if (interaction.commandName === 'ban') {
    const user = interaction.options.getUser('user');
    const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason') || 'No reason provided';

    if (!interaction.member.permissions.has('BAN_MEMBERS')) {
      return interaction.reply({ content: 'You don\'t have permission to ban members!', ephemeral: true });
    }

    if (interaction.member.id === user.id) {
      return interaction.reply({ content: "You can't ban yourself!", ephemeral: true });
    }

    if (!user.bannable) {
      return interaction.reply({ content: 'I cannot ban this user!', ephemeral: true });
    }

    try {
      await interaction.guild.members.ban(user, { reason });
      interaction.reply({ content: ` Successfully banned \`${user.tag}\` for \`${reason}\`.` });
    } catch (error) {
      console.error(error);
      interaction.reply({ content: 'An error occurred while banning the user!', ephemeral: true });
    }
  }
});

client.login(token);
```

5. Create a `config.json` file in the same directory with the following content (replace placeholders with your actual values):

```json
{
  "token": "YOUR_BOT_TOKEN",
  "clientId": "YOUR_CLIENT_ID",
  "guildId": "YOUR_GUILD_ID"
}
```

6. Run your bot with `node index.js`.

Now, your Discord bot should be up and running, listening for the `/ban` command in your specified guild. Users with the appropriate permissions can use the command to ban other members with a reason. Note that this code doesn't include any advanced error handling or permission checks beyond the basic requirements for the `/ban` command.

To create a C++ function that converts Markdown to HTML, you can write a simple parser using the `std::string` manipulations. However, keep in mind that this is a basic implementation, and it will not cover all possible Markdown syntax or edge cases. For a more comprehensive solution, consider using a dedicated markdown parsing library like `cmark`, `hoedown`, `cpp-markdown`, or `hďamoamlab/markdown-cpp`.

Here's a simple C++ function that converts a subset of Markdown to HTML:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdownText) {
    std::string htmlText = markdownText;

    // Headers
    std::regex headerRegex(R"((^#+\s+.+?\n?)|(\n\s*#+\s*))");
    htmlText = std::regex_replace(htmlText, headerRegex, "<h$1>$2</h$1>");

    // Bold text
    std::regex boldRegex(R"(\*\*(.*?)\*\*)");
    htmlText = std::regex_replace(htmlText, boldRegex, "<strong>$1</strong>");

    // Italic text
    std::regex italicRegex(R"(\*(.*?)\*)");
    htmlText = std::regex_replace(htmlText, italicRegex, "<em>$1</em>");

    // Links
    std::regex linkRegex(R"\[(.*?)\]\((https?|ftp)://([^)]+)\)");
    htmlText = std::regex_replace(htmlText, linkRegex, "<a href=\"$2://$3\">$1</a>");

    // Unordered list
    std::regex ulRegex(R"(\n\s*-\s+.+?\n?)");
    htmlText = std::regex_replace(htmlText, ulRegex, "<ul><li>$1</li></ul>");

    // Ordered list
    std::regex olRegex(R"(\n\s*[0-9]+\.\s+.+?\n?)");
    htmlText = std::regex_replace(htmlText, olRegex, "<ol><li>$1</li></ol>");

    // Remove preceding and trailing whitespaces
    htmlText = std::regex_replace(htmlText, R"(\A\s+|\s+\Z)", "");

    return htmlText;
}
```

You can use this function as follows:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Header\n\n*Bold* and _italic_\n\n[Google](https://www.google.com)\n\n- List item\n- Another item\n\n1. Ordered item\n2. Another ordered item";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This function converts the following Markdown features to HTML:

1. Headers (`#` for H1 to H6)
